---
import Base from '../layouts/Base.astro';
---

<Base
  title="About — DeviceLab"
  description="DeviceLab ranks laptops, tablets and desktop PCs on six axes with weights you set yourself. No sponsored order, deterministic scoring."
>
  <section class="dl-page-header">
    <div class="dl-eyebrow-hero">DEVICELAB / ABOUT</div>
    <h1>The device leaderboard <br />you can weigh yourself.</h1>
    <p class="dl-blurb">
      No sponsored order. Six axes, deterministic scoring, and a mixer
      that recomputes the board instantly.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section class="dl-container" style="padding: 12px 16px 40px; max-width: 68ch;">
    <h2>Why we built this</h2>
    <p>
      Buying a laptop, tablet, or desktop in 2026 means wading through
      a hundred near-identical reviews, each with a different score on
      a different scale, all optimised for search-engine ranking rather
      than helping you decide. The mix that matters — how much
      performance vs. how much battery vs. how much price — is
      different for every person, and no static "Top 10 laptops of the
      year" list can capture that.
    </p>
    <p>
      DeviceLab flips it: <strong>you</strong> tell us what matters, we
      tell you which device wins under your mix. Six axes,
      deterministic scoring, and a live ranking that recomputes as you
      nudge the sliders. There is no editorial "we think the X is
      best." The scoring engine is a pure function of your weights and
      the axis scores; you can read it in
      <span class="mono">src/lib/scoring.ts</span> if you want.
    </p>

    <h2>How we score</h2>
    <ul>
      <li>Six axes: performance, portability, display, battery, build, value.</li>
      <li>Each device is rated 0–100 per axis.</li>
      <li>
        Value isn't editorial — it's derived from
        performance-per-£, min-max normalised across the whole catalogue
        to 30–100. Better perf per pound = higher value score.
        Automatic.
      </li>
      <li>The composite is a normalised weighted mean of your weights × the axis scores.</li>
      <li>Ties break on value, then alphabetically.</li>
      <li>
        Rank deltas (▲/▼) show how a device jumps or drops when you
        change weights — useful for stress-testing your priorities
        against the shortlist.
      </li>
    </ul>

    <h2>How it's funded</h2>
    <p>
      DeviceLab is funded by affiliate commission. Some outbound
      retail links — Amazon (UK + US) and, once approved, manufacturer
      links via Awin — are tagged with our affiliate IDs. If you click
      through and buy something, we earn a small percentage from the
      retailer, at no cost to you. Full detail on the
      <a href="/disclosure/">affiliate disclosure</a> page.
    </p>
    <p>
      <strong>Nothing about the ranking depends on that.</strong> The
      code separates scoring from monetisation by design: the scoring
      module has zero imports from the retail-links module. A merchant
      offering more commission for a higher rank would have to
      convince us to change the scoring code, which we won't.
    </p>

    <h2>What we don't do</h2>
    <ul>
      <li>No sponsored placements or "featured" positions.</li>
      <li>No paid inclusion in the catalogue.</li>
      <li>No editorial partnerships that touch the score.</li>
      <li>No third-party analytics or advertising cookies. There is no Google Analytics, no Meta Pixel.</li>
      <li>No email newsletter. "Track price" sends one email when the target hits, then stops.</li>
    </ul>

    <h2>Personas</h2>
    <p>
      The six personas — Overall / Value / Creator / Gamer / Student /
      Business — are named weight vectors that prewire the mixer to
      what a specific shopper typically cares about. They're a
      starting point, not the answer: slide any axis to override, and
      the persona flips to "Custom" the moment you touch it.
    </p>

    <h2>Lines and pairings</h2>
    <p>
      When you filter to a single brand, a line strip appears
      underneath the personas (ThinkPad, Yoga, Legion, IdeaPad, and so
      on). Each line has editorial context — "Business-grade: legendary
      keyboards, MIL-SPEC durability" — and a suggested persona weight
      mix that a user shopping that line probably wants. One tap and
      the mixer flips to those weights.
    </p>

    <h2>Price tracking</h2>
    <p>
      "Track price" opens a one-time email capture that stores
      (email, device, target price) in Cloudflare KV. When the price
      pipeline lands, a scheduled job will diff incoming price points
      against saved targets and send at most one email per trigger.
      Not a newsletter. Full detail on the
      <a href="/privacy/">privacy page</a>.
    </p>

    <h2>Who runs this</h2>
    <p>
      DeviceLab is built and maintained by an independent operator —
      not a media company, not an agency. If you want to reach us for
      corrections, additions, or partnership queries, the
      <a href="/contact/">contact page</a> has an inbox.
    </p>

    <h2>Roadmap markers in the code</h2>
    <p>Four integration points are stubbed and marked:</p>
    <ul class="mono" style="font-size: 13px;">
      <li>TODO(ingestion) — where the price-feed job writes offers + real priceHistory.</li>
      <li>TODO(affiliate) — where merchant links get GTIN-matched deep links + tracking params.</li>
      <li>TODO(alerts) — the scheduled consumer that emails matches on target prices.</li>
      <li>TODO(analytics) — swap CLICK_KV for Cloudflare Analytics Engine for SQL-shaped querying.</li>
    </ul>
    <p>
      All four are decoupled from the scoring engine — none of them can
      influence the ranking.
    </p>
  </section>
</Base>
